canvas_summaries.ocr_text: Outpl. 12 ? Po pa Equal Pay for Equal Work. What it means. Same na aSON Sama e At first sight this seems a simple problem, and one that should be easily determined. If a man and a woman, working for the same em ployer, using the same machine or tools, making similar goods, produce the same number of articles in the week, there seems no reason why they should not be paid the same wages. The goods they produce will be sold for the same price, whether made by a man or a woman. On these grounds the case admits clearly of no argu ment, for if the woman is paid less, the employer is obviously taking the difference in earnings between the two. The case of the teachers is especially strong. The women not only take the same training as the men, pass the same examinations, and teach the same subjects, they also teach sewing as an extra, and are able to take classes of boys, whereas it is seldom if ever, that a male teacher takes classes of girls. The matter is however, not quite so simple as it looks, because, although there are cases where men and women do exactly the same work, there are many more where their work is EQUIVALENT rather than equal. There are cases, for example, where part of the work is taken away and given to another worker, so that the woman does only part of the job. For instance three men may have been employed in making an article or part of an article, each man completing all the processes himself.

canvas_summaries.ocr_text: Three women who replace them do one process each, thus, although the three men and the three women com plete the articles between them, no individual is doing the same work as another. It is quite conceivable that the three women, under some such arrangement, might make more of the articles in a given time than the three men, and they would certainly be justified in claiming " equal pay for equal work; " yet their work is not the same, and any agreement made on these terms would not apply to them. Oman US Differences of Payments. Examination of the salaries paid to public officials, teachers, Civil Service Clerks and Post Office employes, shows that a woman usually receives of a man' s salary for equivalent services. In industrial work however, it is more often about 1. The difference is more marked still if we consider the average wages in any woman' s trade, with those earned by the men of the same standard of life for work of equivalent skill. A dressmaker, for example earned( before the war) about 25/- to 30/- as a " hand, " while a carpenter would earn more than twice as much. Yet most women will maintain, that as much skill is re quired in the making of a really good buttonhole as of a window frame. The basis of payment. It is clear then, that the rate of payment is not estimated on the value of services rendered, or in other words" payment for the job, " but on some other basis. The one usually given, is that of the workers' needs and standard of living The determining factor in this case is that the " average " man has a wife and family to support, while the " average " woman has no dependants. While of course it is true that the majority of men have families to provide for, that majority is not perhaps so large as most people imagine. Less than half the men between 20 and 30 are married; yet are paid at the married men' s rate.

canvas_summaries.ocr_text: It is also true that most working women have only themselves to support, yet there must be many who sup port aged parents, younger brothers and sisters, fatherless children and sometimes invalid or crippled husbands. There is likely to be an increase in these classes, owing to the war casualties, so that it may well be, that in future the woman worker who supports only herself will be in the minority. re The needs of the worker. If earnings are based on the needs of the worker, it is necessary to consider how the money is spent. The married man has, first and foremost, to provide himself with food, shelter, clothing and attendance, that is, some one to buy, cook and serve his meals, mend his clothes, clean his house, etc. All these things are needed by every worker. The man usually gets the attendance from his wife without payment and at the expenditure only of her food and clothing. The woman has to pay for them, and this payment cancels the cost of the wife' s maintenance. If she cannot afford to pay for these ser vices, she must do them herself, and so add to her work which in this way becomes more arduous than the man' s. This has been found to be the case with many munition workers, who often prefer to work on night shift" so that they can do the house work during the day. There remains the maintenance of the children, and this falls entirely on the shoulders of the father of the family. His earnings must clearly therefore enable him to house, feed and clothe his children, unless other means are found of doing so. During the war, while the men have been prevented by military service from maintaining their families, the State has undertaken this duty, and, although the maintenance has been in many cases, below that provided by the father when at home and in work, yet it has been regulated on the strictly logical basis of additional bread for each additional mouth, which his earnings were not.

canvas_summaries.ocr_text: During the first fourteen years each child is depend ent, contributes nothing and consumes all. But it must be remembered that, once these fourteen years are over, the child becomes contributory, and from then onward to marriage, gives substantial help to the family purse. Even after marriage, the children almost invariably contribute to their parents' support in old age or illness. These aids are not available to the self- supporting, self- dependent woman worker. If she is ill, she has no wife to nurse her, when she is old, she has no children to support her. Therefore she should be able to save for these event ualities. Does the į of a man' s salary enable her to do this? Does the f? Unfair competition. So long as these unequal standards of payment obtain between men and women, it follows that where women can be EMPLOYED IN THE PLACE OF MEN, whether their work is exactly the same or whether it is adjusted and re arranged, there will be a tendency to employ women, or fix the wages at the women' s rate. Whichever course were taken would without doubt arouse well founded and excusable resentment, not only from the men but from the men' s wives, who would suffer equally with them. The War Cabinet Committee which is now con sidering these complex questions has no light task to perform. It is one of the encouraging and hopeful signs of the new days that are dawning for us, that this and similar questions are being thought out by experienced men and women in the Ministry of Reconstruction and other Committees authorised to advise the Government, and that such matters will no longer be left to the play of blind chance, or unrestricted competition. This has been found to be the case with many munition workers, who often prefer to work on night shift" so that they can do the house work during the day. There remains the maintenance of the children, and this falls entirely on the shoulders of the father of the family. His earnings must clearly therefore enable him to house, feed and clothe his children, unless other means are found of doing so. During the war, while the men have been prevented by military service from maintaining their families, the State has undertaken this duty, and, although the maintenance has been in many cases, below that provided by the father when at home and in work, yet it has been regulated on the strictly logical basis of additional bread for each additional mouth, which his earnings were not.
During the first fourteen years each child is depend ent, contributes nothing and consumes all. But it must be remembered that, once these fourteen years are over, the child becomes contributory, and from then onward to marriage, gives substantial help to the family purse. Even after marriage, the children almost invariably contribute to their parents' support in old age or illness. These aids are not available to the self- supporting, self- dependent woman worker. If she is ill, she has no wife to nurse her, when she is old, she has no children to support her. Therefore she should be able to save for these event ualities. Does the of a man' s salary enable her to do this? Does the f? Unfair competition. So long as these unequal standards of payment obtain between men and women, it follows that where women can be EMPLOYED IN THE PLACE OF MEN, whether their work is exactly the same or whether it is adjusted and re arranged, there will be a tendency to employ women, or fix the wages at the women' s rate. Whichever course were taken would without doubt arouse well founded and excusable resentment, not only from the men but from the men' s wives, who would suffer equally with them. The War Cabinet Committee which is now con sidering these complex questions has no light task to perform. It is one of the encouraging and hopeful signs of the new days that are dawning for us, that this and similar questions are being thought out by experienced men and women in the Ministry of Reconstruction and other Committees authorised to advise the Government, and that such matters will no longer be left to the play of blind chance, or unrestricted competition. If a man and a woman, working for the same em ployer, using the same machine or tools, making similar goods, produce the same number of articles in the week, there seems no reason why they should not be paid the same wages.
On these grounds the case admits clearly of no argu ment, for if the woman is paid less, the employer is obviously taking the difference in earnings between the two.
The difference is more marked still if we consider the average wages in any woman' s trade, with those earned by the men of the same standard of life for work of equivalent skill.
It is also true that most working women have only themselves to support, yet there must be many who sup port aged parents, younger brothers and sisters, fatherless children and sometimes invalid or crippled husbands.
It is one of the encouraging and hopeful signs of the new days that are dawning for us, that this and similar questions are being thought out by experienced men and women in the Ministry of Reconstruction and other Committees authorised to advise the Government, and that such matters will no longer be left to the play of blind chance, or unrestricted competition.

Po pa Equal Pay for Equal Work.
If a man and a woman, working for the same em ployer, using the same machine or tools, making similar goods, produce the same number of articles in the week, there seems no reason why they should not be paid the same wages.
The one usually given, is that of the workers' needs and standard of living The determining factor in this case is that the " average " man has a wife and family to support, while the " average " woman has no dependants.
Even after marriage, the children almost invariably contribute to their parents' support in old age or illness.
These aids are not available to the self- supporting, self- dependent woman worker.

The matter is however, not quite so simple as it looks, because, although there are cases where men and women do exactly the same work, there are many more where their work is EQUIVALENT rather than equal.
Three women who replace them do one process each, thus, although the three men and the three women com plete the articles between them, no individual is doing the same work as another.
It is quite conceivable that the three women, under some such arrangement, might make more of the articles in a given time than the three men, and they would certainly be justified in claiming " equal pay for equal work; " yet their work is not the same, and any agreement made on these terms would not apply to them.
